:::summary
Rembrandt Harmenszoon van Rijn (1606–1669) was the greatest master of the Dutch Golden Age and, by the judgment of most art historians, one of the two or three supreme painters in Western history. Celebrated above all for his extraordinary command of light and shadow (*chiaroscuro*), his psychological depth, and his compassionate humanity, Rembrandt painted portraits, biblical scenes, mythological subjects, and self-portraits with a technique and emotional power that have never been surpassed. His roughly 40 surviving self-portraits — tracking his own face from ambitious young man to ruined old age — constitute one of the most remarkable autobiographies in art.
:::

